In this notebook, we will implement the first Visual Transformer, ViT. We'll implement a naive version of it, much smaller than the ones described in the paper, and we also won't use complex data augmentation and regularizations. But note that this is important to make transformers work in practice on large-scale dataset.

To get a gist of what is required to make a transformer work in practice, have a look at the DeiT and CaiT codebase.

This notebook is a simplified version of the excellent Timm library.

Here is the general architecture of the ViT model¶

The architecture includes:¶

  • A step for splitting the image into disjoint patches with a linear projection of the patches
  • Positional encoding to capture the absolute spatial information of each patch in the image
  • The addition of a "[CLS]" token, initialized randomly and learned during training
  • A transformer encoder that learns the representation of each token
  • A classification head that performs class prediction from the re-embedded [CLS] token at the output of the encoder

Linear Projection of flattened patches¶

Q1: First, we need to code the patch embedding. In NLP, it could be using a word2vec embeddings, but we need something different in Computer Vision.

You are going to use a specific 2d convolution to play the role of the so-called "Linear Projection" on the image above and process each patch independently without overlap. Think a bit how you could do that.

Then, you need to manipulate the dimensions of the resulting tensor to get a final tensor of shape (batch_size, nb_tokens, embedding_dim). Hint: You will need a view/reshape and transpose/permute operators.

As usual, remember to check the output shape of your layer by trying with a random tensor!

In [24]:
class PatchEmbed(nn.Module):
  def __init__(self, in_chan=1, patch_size=7, embed_dim=128):
    super().__init__()
    ## TODO
    self.patch_size = patch_size
    self.projection = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=in_chan, out_channels=embed_dim, kernel_size=patch_size, stride=patch_size)

  def forward(self, x):
    x = self.projection(x)

    B, C, H, W = x.shape
    ## TODO


    # x.shape() -> B, N, C
    N = H * W #no need to divide by P because it's already done in convolution

    x = x.flatten(2) # flatten from B, C, H, W -> (B, C, H*W)
    x = x.permute(0, 2, 1) #  (B, N, C)

    assert x.shape[0]==B and x.shape[1]==N and x.shape[2]==C, f"Wrong shape : {(B,N,C)} VS {(x.shape[0],x.shape[1],x.shape[2])}"

    return x

Transformer encoder¶

Q2: MLP¶

Now we need to build a transformer block. Let's first build the easiest part, the MLP! By now, you should be confident how to code one.

Code a MLP with one hidden layer. Note that the input and output dimensions will be the same. Instead of ReLU, use the activation GELU, which is a slight alternative often used for transformers.

In [26]:
class MLP(nn.Module):
  def __init__(self, in_features, hid_features):
    super().__init__()
    self.in_features = in_features
    self.hid_features = hid_features
    self.input = nn.Linear(self.in_features, self.hid_features)
    self.activ = nn.GELU()
    self.output = nn.Linear(self.hid_features, self.in_features)

  def forward(self, x):
    # TODO
    x = self.output(self.activ(self.input(x)))
    return x

Q3: Self-attention¶

Now we are going to build the famous Self-Attention.

  • What is the main feature of self-attention, especially compared to its convolutional counterpart. What is its main challenge in terms of computation/memory?
  • At first, we are going to only consider the simple case of one head. Write the equations and complete the following code. And don't forget a final linear projection at the end!
In [27]:
class SelfAttention(nn.Module):
  def __init__(self, embed_dim):
    super().__init__()

    # TODO
    self.embed_dim = embed_dim
    self.WQ = nn.Linear(self.embed_dim, self.embed_dim)
    self.WK = nn.Linear(self.embed_dim, self.embed_dim)
    self.WV = nn.Linear(self.embed_dim, self.embed_dim)
    self.lin_projection = nn.Linear(self.embed_dim, self.embed_dim)
    self.scale = self.embed_dim ** -0.5

  def forward(self, x):
    B, N, C = x.shape

    # TODO: compute the Q, K, V
    q = self.WQ(x)
    k = self.WK(x)
    v = self.WV(x)

    # TODO: compute the attention matrix using Q and K
    attention = F.softmax(torch.matmul(q, k.transpose(-2, -1))*self.scale, dim=-1)

    # TODO: compute the final version using the attention,
    # V, and the final projection
    x = torch.matmul(attention, v)
    x = self.lin_projection(x)
    return x

Q4 : Multi-head self-attention¶

Now we need to build a Multi-Heads Self-Attention.

  • Write the equations and complete the following code to build a Multi-Heads Self-Attention.
  • The total embedding size will be shared equally among all heads.
In [28]:
class MultiHeadsSelfAttention(nn.Module):
  def __init__(self, embed_dim, num_heads):
    super().__init__()

    self.embed_dim = embed_dim
    head_dim =  embed_dim // num_heads
    self.head_dim = head_dim
    self.scale = head_dim ** -0.5
    self.num_heads = num_heads

    self.q = nn.Linear(self.embed_dim, self.embed_dim)
    self.k = nn.Linear(self.embed_dim, self.embed_dim)
    self.v = nn.Linear(self.embed_dim, self.embed_dim)
    self.projection = nn.Linear(self.embed_dim, self.embed_dim)

  def forward(self, x):
    B, N, C = x.shape

    q = self.q(x) # B, N, C
    k = self.k(x) # B, N, C
    v = self.v(x) # B, N, C

    # You need to reshape and permute dimension in a certain manner
    # so that each head (C // num_heads) interact
    # only with its dimensions and not other heads.

    # Try to write at each operation the shape of the tensor if you
    # feel confused.

    # TODO
    q = q.view(B, N, self.num_heads, self.head_dim).permute(0, 2, 1, 3) # B, num_heads, N, head_dim
    k = k.view(B, N, self.num_heads, self.head_dim).permute(0, 2, 1, 3) # B, num_heads, N, head_dim
    v = v.view(B, N, self.num_heads, self.head_dim).permute(0, 2, 1, 3) # B, num_heads, N, head_dim


    score = torch.matmul(q, k.transpose(-2, -1))* self.scale
    #print(score.shape)

    # shape of k^T -> B, num_heads, head_dim, N
    # shape q * k^T -> B, num_heads, N, N

    attention = F.softmax(score, dim=-1) # B, num_heads, N, N
    #print(attention.shape)

    Z = torch.matmul(attention, v) # B, num_heads, N, head_dim
    #print(Z.shape)


    x = self.projection(Z.view(B, N, C)) # last dim needs to be C in order to be compatible with the projection layer's shape

    return x

x = torch.randn(8, 12, 6) # random tensor to test
MultiHeadsSelfAttention(6, 2)(x).shape

Q5: Transfomer block¶

Now, we need to build a Transformer Block as described in the image below.

  • Write the equations and complete the following code.
  • For the Layer Normalization, use PyTorch LayerNorm: https://pytorch.org/docs/stable/generated/torch.nn.LayerNorm.html

In [29]:
class Block(nn.Module):
  def __init__(self, embed_dim, num_heads=4, mlp_ratio=4):
    super().__init__()

    # TODO
    self.embed_dim = embed_dim
    self.num_heads = num_heads
    self.mlp_ratio = mlp_ratio

    self.norm1 = nn.LayerNorm(embed_dim)
    self.multihead_attention = MultiHeadsSelfAttention(embed_dim, num_heads)
    self.norm2 = nn.LayerNorm(embed_dim)
    self.mlp = MLP(embed_dim, mlp_ratio*embed_dim)

  def forward(self, x):
    # TODO
    n1 = self.norm1(x)
    att = self.multihead_attention(n1)
    n2 = self.norm2(x + att)
    ffn = self.mlp(n2)
    x = ffn + x + att
    return x

Q6: Full ViT model¶

Now you need to build a ViT model based on what you coded in the previous questions. There are additional components that should be coded such as the Class token, Positional embedding and the classification head.

  • Explain what is a Class token and why we use it? \
  • Explain whay is the the positional embedding (PE) and why it is important? \

For PE, you can use a sinusoidal encoding (see below), or fully learned.

Sinusoidal PE¶

In [30]:
def get_positional_embeddings(sequence_length, d):
    result = torch.ones(1,sequence_length, d)
    for i in range(sequence_length):
        for j in range(d):
            result[0][i][j] = np.sin(i / (10000 ** (j / d))) if j % 2 == 0 else np.cos(i / (10000 ** ((j - 1) / d)))
    return result
In [31]:
class ViT(nn.Module):
  def __init__(self, embed_dim, nb_blocks, patch_size, nb_classes=10):
    super().__init__()

    num_patches = (28 // patch_size) ** 2

    self.class_token = nn.Parameter(torch.randn(1,1, embed_dim))
    self.pos_embed = nn.Parameter(get_positional_embeddings(1+num_patches, embed_dim))
    self.patch_embed = PatchEmbed(patch_size=patch_size, embed_dim=embed_dim)

    blocks = []
    for _ in range(nb_blocks):
      blocks.append(
          Block(embed_dim)
      )
    self.blocks = nn.Sequential(*blocks)

    self.norm = nn.LayerNorm(embed_dim)
    self.head = nn.Linear(embed_dim, nb_classes)

  def forward(self, x):
    x = self.patch_embed(x) ## image to patches

    ## concatenating class token

    class_token = self.class_token.repeat(x.shape[0], 1, 1) # repeat it batch size times
    x = torch.cat((class_token, x), dim=1)

    ## adding positional embedding
    x = x + self.pos_embed.repeat(x.shape[0], 1, 1)

    ## forward in the transformer
    x = self.blocks(x)

    ## Normalize the output
    x = self.norm(x)

    #print(x.shape) -> [32, 17, 128]: batch size, sequence_length (1+num_patches), embed_dim
    # using x[:, 0, :] -> the first elem of the 2nd dim contains the cls token
    # bcs we prepend it to the patch tokens
    output = self.head(x[:, 0, :]) ## classification output

    return output


ViT(128, 3, 7)(torch.randn(32, 1, 28, 28)).shape

Q7: Experiment on MNIST!¶

A quick function to evaluate our model:

In [32]:
@torch.no_grad()
def eval_model(model, loader):
  model.eval()
  acc = 0.
  c = 0

  for x, y in loader:
    x, y = x.cuda(), y.cuda()
    yhat = model(x)

    acc += torch.sum(yhat.argmax(dim=1) == y).cpu().item()
    c += len(x)

  model.train()
  return round(100 * acc / c, 2)

And run! Feel free to try other hyperparameters.

    x, y = x.cuda(), y.cuda()

    opt.zero_grad()
    yhat = model(x)
    loss = F.cross_entropy(yhat, y)
    loss.backward()

    opt.step()

    train_loss += loss.item()

  print(f"--- Epoch {epoch} ---")
  print(f"Train loss: {train_loss / len(train_loader)}")
acc = eval_model(model, test_loader)
print(f"Test accuracy: {acc}")

In [33]:
def train_and_evaluate(embed_dim, patch_size, nb_blocks, epochs=10, verbose=True):
    model = ViT(embed_dim, nb_blocks, patch_size).cuda()
    opt = torch.optim.Adam(model.parameters())

    train_losses = []
    test_accuracies = []
    test_losses = []
    train_accuracies = []
    for epoch in range(epochs):
        train_loss = 0.
        train_acc = 0
        train_count = 0
        for x, y in train_loader:
            x, y = x.cuda(), y.cuda()

            opt.zero_grad()
            yhat = model(x)
            loss = F.cross_entropy(yhat, y)
            loss.backward()

            opt.step()

            train_loss += loss.item()
            train_acc += (yhat.argmax(dim=1) == y).sum().item()
            train_count += len(x)

        train_losses.append(train_loss / len(train_loader))
        train_accuracies.append(train_acc / train_count * 100)

        test_loss = 0
        test_acc = 0
        test_count = 0

        with torch.no_grad():
            for x, y in test_loader:
                x, y = x.cuda(), y.cuda()
                yhat = model(x)
                loss = F.cross_entropy(yhat, y)
                test_loss += loss.item()
                test_acc += (yhat.argmax(dim=1) == y).sum().item()
                test_count += len(x)
        test_losses.append(test_loss / len(test_loader))
        test_accuracies.append(test_acc / test_count * 100)

        if verbose:
            print(f"--- Epoch {epoch} ---")
            print(f"Train loss: {train_losses[-1]}")
            print(f"Train Accuracy: {train_accuracies[-1]}")
            print(f"Test loss: {test_losses[-1]}")
            print(f"Test Accuracy: {test_accuracies[-1]}")

    return train_losses, test_losses, train_accuracies, test_accuracies

In [44]:
@torch.no_grad()
def eval_model(model, loader, num_channels=1):
  model.eval()
  acc = 0.
  c = 0
  total_loss = 0.

  for x, y in loader:
    x, y = x.cuda(), y.cuda()
    x = x.repeat(1, 3, 1, 1)  # adapt number of channels to fit in ViT =>  (batch_size, 3, 28, 28)

    yhat = model(x)
    loss = F.cross_entropy(yhat, y)
    total_loss += loss.item() * len(x)

    acc += torch.sum(yhat.argmax(dim=1) == y).cpu().item()
    c += len(x)

  model.train()
  avg_loss = total_loss / c
  accuracy = round(100 * acc / c, 2)
  return accuracy, avg_loss

epochs = 10

opt = torch.optim.Adam(model.parameters())
train_losses = []
test_losses = []
train_acc = []
test_acc = []
for epoch in range(epochs):
  train_loss = 0.
  for x, y in train_loader:
    x, y = x.cuda(), y.cuda()

    opt.zero_grad()
    x = x.repeat(1, 3, 1, 1) # adapt number of channels to fit in ViT =>  (batch_size, 3, 28, 28)
    yhat = model(x)
    loss = F.cross_entropy(yhat, y)
    loss.backward()

    opt.step()

    train_loss += loss.item()

  print(f"--- Epoch {epoch} ---")
  print(f"Train loss: {train_loss / len(train_loader)}")
  train_a, train_l = eval_model(model, train_loader, num_channels=3)
  test_a, test_l = eval_model(model, test_loader, num_channels=3)
  train_losses.append(train_l)
  test_losses.append(test_l)
  train_acc.append(train_a)
  test_acc.append(test_a)

acc = eval_model(model, test_loader, num_channels=3)
print(f"Test accuracy: {acc}")

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(14, 10))
fig.suptitle("Comparison of Non-Pretrained and Pretrained ViT Models", fontsize=16)

# Training Loss
axs[0, 0].plot(train_losses, label="Non-Pretrained", color="blue", linestyle="-")
axs[0, 0].plot(pretrain_losses, label="Pretrained", color="orange", linestyle="--")
axs[0, 0].set_title("Training Loss")
axs[0, 0].set_xlabel("Epoch")
axs[0, 0].set_ylabel("Loss")
axs[0, 0].legend()

# Test Loss
axs[0, 1].plot(test_losses, label="Non-Pretrained", color="blue", linestyle="-")
axs[0, 1].plot(pretest_losses, label="Pretrained", color="orange", linestyle="--")
axs[0, 1].set_title("Test Loss")
axs[0, 1].set_xlabel("Epoch")
axs[0, 1].set_ylabel("Loss")
axs[0, 1].legend()

# Training Accuracy
axs[1, 0].plot(train_acc, label="Non-Pretrained", color="blue", linestyle="-")
axs[1, 0].plot(pretrain_acc, label="Pretrained", color="orange", linestyle="--")
axs[1, 0].set_title("Training Accuracy")
axs[1, 0].set_xlabel("Epoch")
axs[1, 0].set_ylabel("Accuracy")
axs[1, 0].legend()

# Test Accuracy
axs[1, 1].plot(test_acc, label="Non-Pretrained", color="blue", linestyle="-")
axs[1, 1].plot(pretest_acc, label="Pretrained", color="orange", linestyle="--")
axs[1, 1].set_title("Test Accuracy")
axs[1, 1].set_xlabel("Epoch")
axs[1, 1].set_ylabel("Accuracy")
axs[1, 1].legend()

plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0, 1, 0.96])
plt.show()
